and Venus evolved the way it
did, how would we ever be able

00:14:20.130 --> 00:14:22.020 position:56%
to tell the difference between Earth

00:14:22.020 --> 00:14:25.240
at any point along its
evolutionary path, what did it look

00:14:25.240 --> 00:14:27.910
like 4 billion years
ago, 3 billion years?

00:14:27.910 --> 00:14:30.030
What's it going to look
like in the future?

00:14:30.030 --> 00:14:32.600
If we can't tell the
difference between that and Venus

00:14:32.600 --> 00:14:35.860
and what it looked like 4
billion years ago and now

00:14:35.860 --> 00:14:39.860
and into the future, how are we
going to decide, as we look at all

00:14:39.860 --> 00:14:42.890 position:56%
of these vast exoplanets, how are we
going to decide where we want to go

00:14:42.890 --> 00:14:47.460
and where we really want to look
for another Earth-like planet?

00:14:47.460 --> 00:14:49.930
It's my bet that most of those
planets we're finding are going

00:14:49.930 --> 00:14:52.720
to be more like Venus
than more like the Earth.

00:14:52.720 --> 00:14:56.240
So we really need to understand why
Venus turned out the way it did.

00:14:56.240 --> 00:15:00.790
So a very brief description
of expiration of Venus,

00:15:00.790 --> 00:15:04.520
Stephanie said there has been
some early exploration of Venus,

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:07.210
she mentioned the early
Mariner, which was great.

00:15:07.210 --> 00:15:12.090
The Mariner mission that flew by
Venus that was the first mission

00:15:12.090 --> 00:15:14.270
to go by Venus, I didn't
include that here

00:15:14.270 --> 00:15:17.370
because it was pretty minimal as
far as the results we got back.

00:15:17.370 --> 00:15:19.980
But we did get an important
result back from Mariner,

00:15:19.980 --> 00:15:22.780
which was that we knew
the surface was not going

00:15:22.780 --> 00:15:26.040
to be a lovely place
for humans to inhabit.

00:15:26.040 --> 00:15:28.180
We learned that it was
going to be very, very hot.

00:15:28.180 --> 00:15:30.620
Up until that time, there
was a lot of science fiction

00:15:30.620 --> 00:15:32.570
that said it was going
to be very tropical,

00:15:32.570 --> 00:15:34.990
and there were all these
Venusians down there, you know,

00:15:34.990 --> 00:15:37.180
having a great day in the shade.

00:15:37.180 --> 00:15:42.020
But then all of that went
out the window with Mariner.

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:44.960
But Venus really was
a popular destination

00:15:44.960 --> 00:15:47.620 position:56%
for very early exploration in space.

00:15:47.620 --> 00:15:50.570
Partly because Venus is right
next door, it's easy to get to,

00:15:50.570 --> 00:15:52.500
only takes a few months,
four or five months

00:15:52.500 --> 00:15:54.560
to get there in a spacecraft.

00:15:54.560 --> 00:16:00.000
So the Soviet Union really
had a lot of success at Venus.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.840
And the main reason they
had a lot of success is

00:16:02.840 --> 00:16:06.210
that they had a brute
force way of doing things.

00:16:06.210 --> 00:16:09.050
They would build two spacecraft,
they'll build two landers,

00:16:09.050 --> 00:16:10.660
and they'd throw them at Venus.

00:16:10.660 --> 00:16:13.260
And if they didn't work, they'd
learn from that experience

00:16:13.260 --> 00:16:15.430
and they'd throw two more and
then they'd throw two more.

00:16:15.430 --> 00:16:17.700
Every time, they'd
launch two and send them

00:16:17.700 --> 00:16:19.570
out there and see what happened.

00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:20.870
And we learned a lot.

00:16:20.870 --> 00:16:22.260
We learned there's
really high pressure,

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:24.570
we learned it was really hot,
we learned it was corrosive,

00:16:24.570 --> 00:16:27.380
and they learned they had to beef
these things up in order to survive

00:16:27.380 --> 00:16:29.150
and make it to the surface.

00:16:29.150 --> 00:16:34.190
But between 1961 and 1983,
they sent a whole slew

00:16:34.190 --> 00:16:35.490
of these things to Venus.

00:16:35.490 --> 00:16:40.130
And about four or five of them
did really well and lasted

00:16:40.130 --> 00:16:42.260 position:56%
for at least an hour on the surface.

00:16:42.260 --> 00:16:44.030 position:56%
One of them lasted almost two hours.

00:16:44.030 --> 00:16:46.800
And we were able to get some
really basic information

00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:49.980
about what the rocks were
made of in the big planes

00:16:49.980 --> 00:16:52.530
where the landers landed.

00:16:52.530 --> 00:16:57.750
In 1978, the United States decided
to join the game and try Venus.

00:16:57.750 --> 00:17:01.750
We first sent this pioneer
mission included two parts.

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:04.150
The first part was an orbiter.

00:17:04.150 --> 00:17:07.760
And the orbiter went into orbit
at Venus in 1978 and it lasted

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:10.990
until 1992, taking
measurements mainly

00:17:10.990 --> 00:17:14.990
of composition in the
upper atmosphere.

00:17:16.050 --> 00:17:20.330
Also, along with that mission,
we dropped off four probes

00:17:20.330 --> 00:17:21.910
into the Venus atmosphere.

00:17:21.910 --> 00:17:24.310
One was a bigger probe,
the Large Probe,

00:17:24.310 --> 00:17:27.340
and it carried instrumentation
that let us try to measure some

00:17:27.340 --> 00:17:30.100
of the composition as we
descended down through the clouds.

00:17:30.100 --> 00:17:32.930
There were also three
smaller probes that went

00:17:32.930 --> 00:17:35.010
down that didn't have the
same kind of instrumentation.

00:17:35.010 --> 00:17:37.890
They mainly were getting
after temperature and pressure

00:17:37.890 --> 00:17:41.990
as they went down through the
atmosphere to the surface.

00:17:41.990 --> 00:17:44.960
The Large Probe was a good
mission, but it had some issues.

00:17:44.960 --> 00:17:47.230
I'll talk a little bit more
about that in a minute.

00:17:47.230 --> 00:17:52.530
In 1985, the Soviet Union
decided to go back to Venus.

00:17:52.530 --> 00:17:56.430 position:56%
They partnered with the Europeans
to send another one of their landers

00:17:56.430 --> 00:17:58.820
and a couple of balloons.

00:17:58.820 --> 00:18:01.820
The balloons lasted for a couple
of days in the atmosphere,

00:18:01.820 --> 00:18:04.900
floating in the cloud layer, in
that sulfuric acid cloud layer,

00:18:04.900 --> 00:18:07.430
which you can imagine, remember,
sulfuric acid, so it's corrosive,

00:18:07.430 --> 00:18:11.310
so it's going to pretty quickly
eat through your balloon material,

00:18:11.310 --> 00:18:14.010
plus when the balloon goes around
on the back side, it's kind of hard

00:18:14.010 --> 00:18:15.480 position:56%
for it to communicate back to Earth.

00:18:15.480 --> 00:18:17.870
So they lost the balloons
after a couple days.

00:18:17.870 --> 00:18:22.100
But again, some good
information about the cloud layer.

00:18:22.100 --> 00:18:25.560
In 1989, the United States
sent the Magellan mission.

00:18:25.560 --> 00:18:29.970
This was a great mission, carried
a radar system that was able to see

00:18:29.970 --> 00:18:34.340
through the clouds and map
the whole surface of Venus.

00:18:34.340 --> 00:18:35.640
It's a great map.

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:39.640
It's the only map we have of Venus,
so we are very glad to have it.

00:18:39.640 --> 00:18:44.040
But I'll remind you, you know, we
get so spoiled in this modern age,

00:18:44.040 --> 00:18:46.670
we look at the kind of images
we get from Mars with, you know,

00:18:46.670 --> 00:18:48.710
resolutions that are,
you know, like this.

00:18:48.710 --> 00:18:52.960
You can see individual pebbles
and rocks on the surface.

00:18:52.960 --> 00:18:57.600
The Magellan images are the
type of resolution similar to,

00:18:57.600 --> 00:19:01.620
if you go back and look at Viking
images of Mars from the 1970s,

00:19:01.620 --> 00:19:04.410 position:56%
that's what we have for Venus, okay?

00:19:04.410 --> 00:19:06.900
So it's very hard to answer
some of the kinds of questions

00:19:06.900 --> 00:19:08.440
that we now address on Mars

00:19:08.440 --> 00:19:11.430
about actual geologic
processes and geophysics.

00:19:11.430 --> 00:19:14.120
It's hard to answer those
questions with these old data.

00:19:14.120 --> 00:19:15.420
So they're good.

00:19:15.420 --> 00:19:16.720
We're glad to have them.

00:19:16.720 --> 00:19:18.920
But we certainly need
more new data there.

00:19:18.920 --> 00:19:21.960
More recently, the
Europeans have been there,

00:19:21.960 --> 00:19:23.740
been to Venus, with Venus Express.

00:19:23.740 --> 00:19:26.940 position:56%
They had a mission that lasted
about eight years, over eight years,

00:19:26.940 --> 00:19:31.510
that mapped and looked at chemistry
and dynamics in the cloud layers

00:19:31.510 --> 00:19:33.260
and in the upper atmosphere.

00:19:33.260 --> 00:19:34.760
And then as Stephanie mentioned,

00:19:34.760 --> 00:19:38.870
right now is a Japanese
mission called Akatsuki.

00:19:38.870 --> 00:19:40.700
And it was launched in 2010.

00:19:40.700 --> 00:19:42.130
It missed orbit the first time.

00:19:42.130 --> 00:19:43.570
Finally got into orbit in 2015.

00:19:43.570 --> 00:19:45.670
It's a great success
story of perseverance.

00:19:45.670 --> 00:19:49.960 position:56%
They used their little tiny thruster
engines in order to get into orbit.

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:51.320
And so they're there.

00:19:51.320 --> 00:19:55.350 position:56%
And again, making pictures and
taking data of the upper atmosphere,

00:19:55.350 --> 00:19:56.730
looking at cloud dynamics.

00:19:56.730 --> 00:19:59.710
But what I want to draw your
attention to here is to think

00:19:59.710 --> 00:20:06.750
about the last time the United
States went to Venus was 1990ish.

00:20:06.750 --> 00:20:11.390
Again, with instrumentation that
was probably 1970s technology.

00:20:11.390 --> 00:20:12.710
So that's where we are with that

00:20:12.710 --> 00:20:16.830
with the U.S. The last time anyone
went into the atmosphere or down

00:20:16.830 --> 00:20:22.250
to the surface of Venus was in
1985, again, with old technology

00:20:22.250 --> 00:20:24.530
and the kinds of questions
that we need to answer.

00:20:24.530 --> 00:20:27.500
We just don't have the
data available for Venus.

00:20:27.500 --> 00:20:28.800
But what did we learn?

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:30.100
So we learned a lot.

00:20:30.100 --> 00:20:33.120
We did get some answers, but we
also got a lot more new questions.

00:20:33.120 --> 00:20:35.360
But I'll tell you some of
the things we did learn.

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:37.710
One thing we learned, of
course, is that the surface

00:20:37.710 --> 00:20:40.380
of Venus appears to
be very volcanic.

00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:43.860
Most of the surface is covered
in volcanic flows and volcanoes

00:20:43.860 --> 00:20:47.530
and the volcanoes on Venus look
more or less similar to the types

00:20:47.530 --> 00:20:48.830
of things we have on Earth.

00:20:48.830 --> 00:20:52.030
They look like volcanoes that
we understand with lava rocks

00:20:52.030 --> 00:20:54.310
that come out, just
like they do on Earth.

00:20:54.310 --> 00:20:57.430
But the main difference is,
this is Venus here on the left,

00:20:57.430 --> 00:21:02.230
and this is the Magellan
figure showing topography.

00:21:02.230 --> 00:21:03.680
So the blues are not water.

00:21:03.680 --> 00:21:05.910
They're actually very
low-lying areas.

00:21:05.910 --> 00:21:08.330
And the pinks and whites
up here are the high levels

00:21:08.330 --> 00:21:10.600
and the mountains and
things on Venus.

00:21:10.600 --> 00:21:14.230
But what we see on Venus is
that there's no evidence at all

00:21:14.230 --> 00:21:16.550
for plate tectonics
like we have on Earth.

00:21:16.550 --> 00:21:17.850
We have plate tectonics.

00:21:17.850 --> 00:21:19.490
Our plates are all moving around,

00:21:19.490 --> 00:21:21.750
subducting under each other,
riding over each other.

00:21:21.750 --> 00:21:24.560
And that's where most of our
volcanism happens on Earth,

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:27.140
is at those plate boundaries.

00:21:27.140 --> 00:21:28.790
We don't see those plates on Venus.

00:21:28.790 --> 00:21:32.090
We see volcanoes, so they
must be popping up somehow.

00:21:32.090 --> 00:21:38.150
But what we don't know is why
Venus doesn't have plate tectonics

00:21:38.150 --> 00:21:39.450
and Earth does.

00:21:39.450 --> 00:21:40.810
They should both be
hot on their interior.

00:21:40.810 --> 00:21:43.790
They both need to be
losing heat in some way.

00:21:43.790 --> 00:21:46.160
This is plate movements and
the volcanism along the plates,

00:21:46.160 --> 00:21:48.030
that's how we lose
our heat on Earth.

00:21:48.030 --> 00:21:49.350
How is Venus losing its heat?

00:21:49.350 --> 00:21:50.650
It should still be hot.

00:21:50.650 --> 00:21:52.360
Is it still volcanically active?

00:21:52.360 --> 00:21:54.640
And we'll come back to
that one in a minute.

00:21:54.640 --> 00:21:57.590
What does the surface look like?

00:21:57.590 --> 00:22:04.730
We have pictures from four landing
sites from over 30 years ago.

00:22:04.730 --> 00:22:06.380
This is what we have
for the surface.

00:22:06.380 --> 00:22:07.870
This is what we know.

00:22:07.870 --> 00:22:09.170
We've got a couple of these.

00:22:09.170 --> 00:22:11.880
It looks like dried up old lava.

00:22:11.880 --> 00:22:13.220
It looks like a basaltic flow.

00:22:13.220 --> 00:22:15.390
If you went out to Hawaii
and walked around lava flows,

00:22:15.390 --> 00:22:18.610
they kind of look like that.

00:22:18.610 --> 00:22:20.860
So that's what we know of
those four landing sites.

00:22:20.860 --> 00:22:22.950
But because of that
thick cloud layer, again,

00:22:22.950 --> 00:22:28.230 position:56%
the only way we can see the surface
remotely from orbiter is with radar.

00:22:28.230 --> 00:22:29.750
And so that's all we have.

00:22:29.750 --> 00:22:32.280
And that radar sometimes can be
a little difficult to interpret

00:22:32.280 --> 00:22:34.060
with our eyes that are
used to seeing things

00:22:34.060 --> 00:22:35.360
at more optical wavelengths.

00:22:35.360 --> 00:22:37.720
Radar wavelengths are a
little more complicated.

00:22:37.720 --> 00:22:41.240
Other things we've
learned about the surface.

00:22:41.240 --> 00:22:43.060
Again, a lot of questions.

00:22:43.060 --> 00:22:46.030
First, again, about 80%
of the surface appears

00:22:46.030 --> 00:22:48.450
to be covered in these lava flows.

00:22:48.450 --> 00:22:49.890
All right, I'm good so far.

00:22:49.890 --> 00:22:51.340
There appears to be lava flow.

00:22:51.340 --> 00:22:53.040
That makes sense to me.

00:22:53.040 --> 00:22:58.480 position:56%
From what the Soviet landers told us
with their chemistry, we can infer,

00:22:58.480 --> 00:23:01.910 position:56%
we can guess that most of those lava
flows are something we call basalt,

00:23:01.910 --> 00:23:04.620
which is the most primary
kind of volcanic rock.

00:23:04.620 --> 00:23:06.660
It's the kind of volcanic
rock you find in Hawaii.

00:23:06.660 --> 00:23:07.960
It's very primitive.

00:23:07.960 --> 00:23:12.000
It's the kind of rock you find
at the mid ocean ridges on Earth.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:13.330
So that's not terribly surprising.

00:23:13.330 --> 00:23:14.630
That's good.

00:23:14.630 --> 00:23:19.930
But we found fewer than a
thousand impact craters on Venus.

00:23:19.930 --> 00:23:21.230
That's not very many.

00:23:21.230 --> 00:23:24.000
Look at the surface of Mars
and Mercury and the Moon.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:27.960
Thousands, hundreds of thousands
of craters of all sizes.

00:23:27.960 --> 00:23:29.740
You go to Venus, there's less

00:23:29.740 --> 00:23:32.350
than a thousand craters
that can be identified.

00:23:32.350 --> 00:23:33.740
Yes, it has a dense atmosphere.

00:23:33.740 --> 00:23:36.730
Yes, the smaller asteroids
are going to be destroyed.

00:23:36.730 --> 00:23:38.030
But what about the big ones?

00:23:38.030 --> 00:23:39.330
Where's the big ones?

00:23:39.330 --> 00:23:40.800
There's not even any
big basins like you see

00:23:40.800 --> 00:23:42.970
on Mercury and the Moon and Mars.

00:23:42.970 --> 00:23:44.270
They're not there.

00:23:44.270 --> 00:23:45.570
We haven't seen them.

00:23:45.570 --> 00:23:46.870
We don't know.

00:23:46.870 --> 00:23:48.170
They all appear fresh.

00:23:48.170 --> 00:23:49.470
There's not very many of them.

00:23:49.470 --> 00:23:53.290
And so the way this has been
interpreted is number one,

00:23:53.290 --> 00:23:56.690
the surface is pretty young, okay?

00:23:56.690 --> 00:23:59.150
The other thing is
those thousand craters

00:23:59.150 --> 00:24:03.080 position:56%
that have been studied statistically
appear to be randomly distributed

00:24:03.080 --> 00:24:05.820
on the whole surface of
the planet, which tells us

00:24:05.820 --> 00:24:09.000
that the whole surface is
more or less the same age.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:11.590
That's a little weird.

00:24:11.590 --> 00:24:13.430 position:56%
I'm not sure how you do that either.

00:24:13.430 --> 00:24:16.250
So the question is, or what
the assumption has been,

00:24:16.250 --> 00:24:19.500
that this surface is about
500 million years old,

00:24:19.500 --> 00:24:21.550
plus or minus several
hundred million years old,

00:24:21.550 --> 00:24:23.810
but still relatively young.

00:24:23.810 --> 00:24:27.070
And it's all about the same age.

00:24:27.070 --> 00:24:29.440
So one thing that's been
proposed is well, maybe you need

00:24:29.440 --> 00:24:34.230
to constantly be resurfacing that
surface with volcanoes, right?

00:24:34.230 --> 00:24:36.070
With the volcanic lava flows.

00:24:36.070 --> 00:24:39.660
And you can do that either
through constant volcanism,

00:24:39.660 --> 00:24:41.250
which means the surface
was very, very young

00:24:41.250 --> 00:24:44.210
or just turned off
500 million years ago.

00:24:44.210 --> 00:24:48.360
Or you can do it through periodic
overturning events perhaps, right?

00:24:48.360 --> 00:24:51.450
The interior gets really
hot and you've got this lid,

00:24:51.450 --> 00:24:53.600
this stagnant lid trapping
all of that heat,

00:24:53.600 --> 00:24:58.270 position:56%
and then maybe every 500 million or
a billion years, that heat builds up

00:24:58.270 --> 00:25:01.540
and it just turns over and
you get this rapid resurfacing

00:25:01.540 --> 00:25:02.840
of the surface.

00:25:02.840 --> 00:25:06.410 position:56%
But we don't really have enough
information to answer that question.

00:25:06.410 --> 00:25:10.390
We also had these unique
geologic features that we see.

00:25:10.390 --> 00:25:13.190
They're higher than most of
the rest of the topography.

00:25:13.190 --> 00:25:15.860
They're higher than
the basaltic plains.

00:25:15.860 --> 00:25:18.450
And we call them tessera.

00:25:18.450 --> 00:25:23.830 position:56%
Tessera is a Latin word, I believe,
that pretty much describes this kind

00:25:23.830 --> 00:25:27.630
of aparque-like fabric, right,
this crisscrossing tectonic fabric

00:25:27.630 --> 00:25:29.930
that we see in this region.

00:25:29.930 --> 00:25:34.240
And these tessera, we don't
really have any known analog

00:25:34.240 --> 00:25:35.540
in the Solar System.

00:25:35.540 --> 00:25:37.790
We haven't really seen
this anyplace else.

00:25:37.790 --> 00:25:42.990
We don't know where and how you
can get these perpendicular faults

00:25:42.990 --> 00:25:48.420
that are disrupting and
changing the morphology here.

00:25:48.420 --> 00:25:50.980
We don't know how you can do that.

00:25:50.980 --> 00:25:54.300
We also are even further intrigued

00:25:54.300 --> 00:25:56.410
by these things, these
tessera regions.

00:25:56.410 --> 00:25:58.740
Again, they're higher
than everything else.

00:25:58.740 --> 00:26:03.720
If you look at the stratigraphy,
which is looking at the ages

00:26:03.720 --> 00:26:07.320 position:56%
of things, we can look and we can
see that some of the lava flows look

00:26:07.320 --> 00:26:10.270
like they've lapped up against
the edges, which tells us

00:26:10.270 --> 00:26:15.020
that the tessera are older than
the lava flows that surround them.

00:26:15.020 --> 00:26:20.240
So these units might be older
than the basaltic plains.

00:26:20.240 --> 00:26:22.860
They also might have a
slightly different composition.

00:26:22.860 --> 00:26:25.030
They might not be basalt.

00:26:25.030 --> 00:26:26.610
We see from Venus Express,

00:26:26.610 --> 00:26:28.510
I said the only way you
can see the surface is

