We do know there's a lot of
sulfur in Venus's atmosphere.

00:38:25.890 --> 00:38:28.680
It drives all of those
big sulfuric acid clouds.

00:38:28.680 --> 00:38:30.700
But where does all
that sulfur come from?

00:38:30.700 --> 00:38:32.550
Is there a supply of sulfur today?

00:38:32.550 --> 00:38:35.450
Can you supply it just
by weathering the rocks?

00:38:35.450 --> 00:38:38.150
Or do you need some
other active supply

00:38:38.150 --> 00:38:40.250
of sulfur into the atmosphere?

00:38:40.250 --> 00:38:45.480
We come back to is Venus
volcanically active?

00:38:45.480 --> 00:38:48.020
I said there's all of
these unknown questions

00:38:48.020 --> 00:38:51.930
about how does Venus lose its heat?

00:38:51.930 --> 00:38:57.490
Does it still have active
volcanoes that are putting material

00:38:57.490 --> 00:38:59.860
out onto the surface
and into the atmosphere?

00:38:59.860 --> 00:39:01.640
And if it is, could we tell?

00:39:01.640 --> 00:39:04.270
I will tell you we've been
going to Venus now, you saw,

00:39:04.270 --> 00:39:09.150
since the early 1970s, and we
have yet to see a smoking gun.

00:39:09.150 --> 00:39:11.380
We've got hints, and I'm going to
show you those in just a second,

00:39:11.380 --> 00:39:14.220
but we haven't seen anything that
we can say yes, gosh darn it,

00:39:14.220 --> 00:39:17.250
Venus is volcanically active,
it's erupting right now today.

00:39:17.250 --> 00:39:18.550
We don't know.

00:39:18.550 --> 00:39:21.370
But again, should be hot inside,
should be losing its heat,

00:39:21.370 --> 00:39:23.470
should be volcanically active.

00:39:23.470 --> 00:39:29.980
So let's talk about some of the
evidence, circumstantial evidence

00:39:29.980 --> 00:39:33.900
that we have that maybe
Venus is volcanically active.

00:39:33.900 --> 00:39:36.880
This chart over here
starts with a peak here.

00:39:36.880 --> 00:39:41.610
This is when Pioneer Venus
orbiter arrived at Venus in 1978.

00:39:41.610 --> 00:39:42.910
And it started taking measurements

00:39:42.910 --> 00:39:46.150
of sulfur dioxide above
the Venus clouds.

00:39:46.150 --> 00:39:49.170
And then you saw a spike, and
then it dropped off exponentially

00:39:49.170 --> 00:39:50.700
over the lifetime of Pioneer Venus.

00:39:50.700 --> 00:39:52.610
And then we have a big gap
because nobody was at Venus.

00:39:52.610 --> 00:39:57.110
And then Venus Express showed up
and they saw another big spike

00:39:57.110 --> 00:40:00.370 position:56%
in sulfur dioxide and another decay,
and maybe another little spike,

00:40:00.370 --> 00:40:02.930
maybe, and then more decay.

00:40:02.930 --> 00:40:07.180
So these spikes, what causes
spikes in sulfur dioxide

00:40:07.180 --> 00:40:08.480
at the top of the atmosphere?

00:40:08.480 --> 00:40:12.910
I mean, these are at 70
kilometers 43 miles up.

00:40:12.910 --> 00:40:14.210
That's pretty darn high.

00:40:14.210 --> 00:40:17.790
Well, on Earth, what causes
pulses in sulfur dioxide

00:40:17.790 --> 00:40:19.970
at the cloud tops is volcanoes.

00:40:19.970 --> 00:40:22.890
Volcanoes emit a lot
of sulfur dioxide.

00:40:22.890 --> 00:40:25.730
Notable examples are Pinatubo
shown here on the right.

00:40:25.730 --> 00:40:27.030
This is not the big one.

00:40:27.030 --> 00:40:28.330
This is not the big eruption.

00:40:28.330 --> 00:40:29.630
This was the day before
the big eruption.

00:40:29.630 --> 00:40:31.720
The actual big eruption,
they were having a typhoon,

00:40:31.720 --> 00:40:33.960
so there's not very many
good pictures of that.

00:40:33.960 --> 00:40:35.260
And people were running away.

00:40:35.260 --> 00:40:37.360
Not in pictures.

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:40.490
But Pinatubo put an enormous
amount of sulfur dioxide

00:40:40.490 --> 00:40:43.150
into the atmosphere, and
that sulfur converted

00:40:43.150 --> 00:40:44.950
into sulfuric acid aerosols,

00:40:44.950 --> 00:40:48.910
and it actually changed the
weather regionally for a period

00:40:48.910 --> 00:40:51.270
of about two or three years, okay?

00:40:51.270 --> 00:40:53.350
Cooled off the surface.

00:40:53.350 --> 00:40:55.810
Warmed the stratosphere,
cooled the surface.

00:40:55.810 --> 00:40:57.680
So is this happening on Venus?

00:40:57.680 --> 00:41:00.940
Well, on Earth, the largest
plumes, the largest volcanoes,

00:41:00.940 --> 00:41:04.540
the plumes that rise in the
atmosphere go to about 20

00:41:04.540 --> 00:41:07.140
to 25 miles in the atmosphere.

00:41:07.140 --> 00:41:10.110
And as Stephanie said, this was an
area, this was how I got into Venus

00:41:10.110 --> 00:41:11.530
because I love volcanoes.

00:41:11.530 --> 00:41:12.830
That's how I started.

00:41:12.830 --> 00:41:14.130
That's what I was studying.

00:41:14.130 --> 00:41:16.050
And all of a sudden, I saw this
on Venus and I thought, how cool,

00:41:16.050 --> 00:41:18.120
are there really active
volcanoes on Venus?

00:41:18.120 --> 00:41:21.090
So I started modeling
volcanic plumes on Venus.

00:41:21.090 --> 00:41:25.130
And what I found is that
it is extremely difficult

00:41:25.130 --> 00:41:30.180
to have a convecting buoyant plume
in Venus's atmosphere because it's

00:41:30.180 --> 00:41:33.660 position:56%
so hot, the atmosphere is so hot and
so dense, it's very hard to do that.

00:41:33.660 --> 00:41:37.560
I'm not saying it's impossible, but
it's very difficult to do on Venus,

00:41:37.560 --> 00:41:41.960
to drive sulfur dioxide all the
way to the top of the clouds.

00:41:41.960 --> 00:41:45.510
So where we are left with, okay,
maybe it's volcanoes, maybe,

00:41:45.510 --> 00:41:47.580
but there are other hypotheses.

00:41:47.580 --> 00:41:50.750
You could actually have just
random periodic overturn events

00:41:50.750 --> 00:41:52.050
in the cloud layer.

00:41:52.050 --> 00:41:55.750
We know that beneath the sulfuric
acid, just below the clouds,

00:41:55.750 --> 00:41:58.240
there is kind of a reservoir
of sulfur dioxide there.

00:41:58.240 --> 00:41:59.540
That's where it accumulates.

00:41:59.540 --> 00:42:01.330
And so if there were
just a random overturn,

00:42:01.330 --> 00:42:03.890
you would get a little pulse
of sulfur coming up to the top.

00:42:03.890 --> 00:42:07.450
You could have even had a meteorite
disturb it and cause that overturn.

00:42:07.450 --> 00:42:08.750
So there's other hypotheses.

00:42:08.750 --> 00:42:12.000
Volcanism isn't the only
answer, although very tempting

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:13.500
to want to go that route.

00:42:13.500 --> 00:42:18.140
Other possible evidence of
active volcanoes on Venus,

00:42:18.140 --> 00:42:22.010
I mentioned that the Venus Express
instrument had an infrared camera

00:42:22.010 --> 00:42:24.310
that had one channel that could
see all the way to the surface

00:42:24.310 --> 00:42:28.500
and measure the reflectivity
of the surface, the emissivity.

00:42:28.500 --> 00:42:30.390
And they've seen some anomalies.

00:42:30.390 --> 00:42:37.980
These are some high emissivities,
so low reflectivity over a volcano

00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:42.340
in southern Venus hemisphere
that they associate with

00:42:42.340 --> 00:42:46.430
or have interpreted it to be
associated with young volcanics,

00:42:46.430 --> 00:42:49.530
unweathered volcanics, which
doesn't mean yesterday young,

00:42:49.530 --> 00:42:50.940
it means thousands of years young.

00:42:50.940 --> 00:42:55.180
But basically unweathered
material that could be present

00:42:55.180 --> 00:42:57.980
at a currently active volcano.

00:42:57.980 --> 00:43:00.560
More recently, there was a study
published where they saw one

00:43:00.560 --> 00:43:03.690
of these emissivity
anomalies not there,

00:43:03.690 --> 00:43:05.210
there it is, now it's not there.

00:43:05.210 --> 00:43:08.170
Is this a thermal signal

00:43:08.170 --> 00:43:11.300
from an actual active
lava flow on the surface?

00:43:11.300 --> 00:43:16.080
Maybe. It is associated with a
volcano, but then a lot of things

00:43:16.080 --> 00:43:18.660
on the surface of Venus are
associated with volcanoes.

00:43:18.660 --> 00:43:20.910
And there's a lot of modeling
involved and a lot of things

00:43:20.910 --> 00:43:24.540
that have to happen in order to
pull out this little tiny signal.

00:43:24.540 --> 00:43:25.840
So there's still a lot of debate.

00:43:25.840 --> 00:43:28.950
Is this really, is this
anomaly real or is it not real,

00:43:28.950 --> 00:43:31.910
is it just a variability in
the clouds or what is it?

00:43:31.910 --> 00:43:34.560
But it's tempting,
it's really tempting

00:43:34.560 --> 00:43:38.100
to say we've seen active volcanism,
but as of yet, we haven't been able

00:43:38.100 --> 00:43:41.900
to say here is a place where there
wasn't a lava flow, you know,

00:43:41.900 --> 00:43:44.090
back when Magellan flew,
and here today is a place

00:43:44.090 --> 00:43:46.110
where there is a new lava
flow that wasn't there before.

00:43:46.110 --> 00:43:48.240
Haven't seen it yet.

00:43:48.240 --> 00:43:51.340
All right, so I have
hopefully now convinced you

00:43:51.340 --> 00:43:56.390 position:56%
that Venus is a fascinating place
with lots of things we need to know,

00:43:56.390 --> 00:43:58.810
and that yes, there have been
some good missions to Venus,

00:43:58.810 --> 00:44:01.690
but we're still, we've got so
many questions, and there's still

00:44:01.690 --> 00:44:05.430 position:56%
so many things that we need to know,
that need to be measured at Venus.

00:44:05.430 --> 00:44:09.460
So let me talk a little bit about
NASA's programs and NASA's plans

00:44:09.460 --> 00:44:13.030
