and [inaudible] composition
investigation.

00:51:09.100 --> 00:51:11.360
So that one is in competition.

00:51:11.360 --> 00:51:15.300 position:56%
We should know in between October
and December will be an announcement

00:51:15.300 --> 00:51:18.950
from NASA headquarters indicating
which of those 13 or so missions

00:51:18.950 --> 00:51:21.810
or down selected for
additional study.

00:51:21.810 --> 00:51:23.600
We've got our fingers
crossed that at least one

00:51:23.600 --> 00:51:26.010
of those three Venus
missions will get selected.

00:51:26.010 --> 00:51:30.870
You know, I've invested a lot
in mine, and I'm very partial

00:51:30.870 --> 00:51:34.110
to my mission, but I'm
also more partial to Venus.

00:51:34.110 --> 00:51:37.180
And so what I really want to
see is a mission to Venus.

00:51:37.180 --> 00:51:39.700
All of the scientists that have
proposed the Venus missions

00:51:39.700 --> 00:51:41.000
are excellent.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:42.370
All the missions are good.

00:51:42.370 --> 00:51:44.080
We just have to get
one one of these days.

00:51:44.080 --> 00:51:48.700
We will. Outside of NASA,
what's thinking about Venus?

00:51:48.700 --> 00:51:50.120
Who wants to go back to Venus?

00:51:50.120 --> 00:51:54.450
Well, Europeans have had this very
successful Venus Express mission.

00:51:54.450 --> 00:51:56.710
And so they're already going
back to the drawing table.

00:51:56.710 --> 00:52:00.390 position:56%
They said, well, with Venus Express,
we focused a lot on the atmosphere

00:52:00.390 --> 00:52:03.500
and understanding the chemistry
and dynamics of the atmosphere.

00:52:03.500 --> 00:52:04.800
What's next?

00:52:04.800 --> 00:52:08.370
And so the Europeans are also very
interested in an orbiting mission

00:52:08.370 --> 00:52:10.380
with a radar, carrying a radar

00:52:10.380 --> 00:52:13.840
that can do higher resolution
imaging and get topography.

00:52:13.840 --> 00:52:17.280
Their mission is called ENVISION,
and that is also currently

00:52:17.280 --> 00:52:19.950
under competition in
their M class category,

00:52:19.950 --> 00:52:21.910
which is their medium
class category,

00:52:21.910 --> 00:52:23.550
which is a little bigger
than our medium class.

00:52:23.550 --> 00:52:26.940
But it's a good size mission.

00:52:26.940 --> 00:52:28.240
But it's under competition.

00:52:28.240 --> 00:52:30.580
We don't know where
that stands right now.

00:52:30.580 --> 00:52:34.650
And Russia is also
currently thinking

00:52:34.650 --> 00:52:39.600
about a potential new mission
to Venus, a new Venera mission.

00:52:39.600 --> 00:52:43.930 position:56%
It's called Venera D. And do not ask
me to pronounce the word that begins

00:52:43.930 --> 00:52:45.460
with D because I cannot do it.

00:52:45.460 --> 00:52:49.110
But it means long lived, which
means hopefully will last longer

00:52:49.110 --> 00:52:50.800
than one hour on the surface.

00:52:50.800 --> 00:52:53.670
It should last maybe five
hours on the surface.

00:52:53.670 --> 00:52:54.970
How exciting.

00:52:54.970 --> 00:52:57.810
And there's no commitment
from the Russian government

00:52:57.810 --> 00:52:59.110
to fly this mission.

00:52:59.110 --> 00:53:04.420
But the Russian Space Agency and
NASA are working together right now

00:53:04.420 --> 00:53:08.260
to define what the science is
that this mission would do.

00:53:08.260 --> 00:53:11.960 position:56%
So we are working on a joint science
definition team with the Russians

00:53:11.960 --> 00:53:15.290
and trying to map out if
we ever could get support

00:53:15.290 --> 00:53:17.360
from all the relevant governments,

00:53:17.360 --> 00:53:20.250
could we fly another
mission led by the Russians?

00:53:20.250 --> 00:53:23.440
This mission that they're thinking
about would include an orbiter,

00:53:23.440 --> 00:53:27.990
a sub orbiter, a lander, and
maybe some aerial platforms,

00:53:27.990 --> 00:53:30.760
which aerial platforms could
mean a balloon or an airplane

00:53:30.760 --> 00:53:32.850
or something flying
in the cloud layer.

00:53:32.850 --> 00:53:35.150
So it's a pretty aggressive
plan right now.

00:53:35.150 --> 00:53:36.910
And at this point,
as I said, no funding

00:53:36.910 --> 00:53:39.610
or any dollars really
associated with it.

00:53:39.610 --> 00:53:43.790
But the scientific community,
there's no lack of interest

00:53:43.790 --> 00:53:45.120
from the scientific community.

00:53:45.120 --> 00:53:48.000
It's trying to get the
agencies and the governments

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:50.020
to put some money behind
it and make it happen.

00:53:50.020 --> 00:53:53.490
So with that, I think I'm going
to wrap this up a little bit.

00:53:53.490 --> 00:53:58.110
The key things I really want you to
walk away with today, number one,

00:53:58.110 --> 00:54:00.290
Venus is very similar to Earth.

00:54:00.290 --> 00:54:01.790
It was similar to Earth.

00:54:01.790 --> 00:54:04.050
They started out, we
think, very similar.

00:54:04.050 --> 00:54:07.760
But somewhere along the
way, something happened.

00:54:07.760 --> 00:54:11.060
Somewhere they diverged and
they became very different

00:54:11.060 --> 00:54:15.050
in their climates and in
their surfaces and in their--

00:54:15.050 --> 00:54:17.030
in so many different ways.

00:54:17.030 --> 00:54:22.600
We don't understand when or why
that happened, but we need to.

00:54:22.600 --> 00:54:25.540
We need to if we want to
understand how these rocky planets

00:54:25.540 --> 00:54:29.430
with atmospheres, how they
form, how they evolve over time.

00:54:29.430 --> 00:54:32.850
How did that work even in our own
Solar System with our little suite

00:54:32.850 --> 00:54:34.960
of Venus, Earth and Mars?

00:54:34.960 --> 00:54:36.700
We've got three N members there.

00:54:36.700 --> 00:54:38.000
We're missing one.

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:39.300
We know Mars pretty well.

00:54:39.300 --> 00:54:40.770
We don't know Venus.

00:54:40.770 --> 00:54:42.070
We need to do that.

00:54:42.070 --> 00:54:44.030
If we're going to understand
and interpret the exoplanets

00:54:44.030 --> 00:54:45.330
that we're discovering,

00:54:45.330 --> 00:54:49.070
we're missing some important
information on Venus.

00:54:49.070 --> 00:54:52.500
Another thing to walk away
with is right now, as of today,

00:54:52.500 --> 00:54:55.970
there are no planned
Venus missions of any kind

00:54:55.970 --> 00:54:58.730
by any country right now.

00:54:58.730 --> 00:55:00.800
Lots of things in the works, but
there have been lots of things

00:55:00.800 --> 00:55:02.210
in the works for many, many years.

00:55:02.210 --> 00:55:05.870
We did a count the other day
within NASA competed programs.

00:55:05.870 --> 00:55:10.850
Venus is 26 and 0, 26
proposals and 0 wins.

00:55:10.850 --> 00:55:17.750
So, you know, new love for
Venus so we can get back there.

00:55:17.750 --> 00:55:26.190
So my last pitch to you is that,
for me, what I think we really need

00:55:26.190 --> 00:55:30.950 position:56%
to do to get back to Venus is really
get back into Venus's atmosphere.

00:55:30.950 --> 00:55:34.740
The missions that have been to
Venus's atmosphere, the Veneras,

00:55:34.740 --> 00:55:38.430
the Pioneer Venus, Large
Probe, they got us started,

00:55:38.430 --> 00:55:41.700
but they really left us with
more questions than answers.

00:55:41.700 --> 00:55:46.070
We've had, since 1978, I
think I wrote it down here

00:55:46.070 --> 00:55:50.320
so I wouldn't forget, six orbital
missions, six orbital missions.

00:55:50.320 --> 00:55:54.050
It's time to get back
into Venus's atmosphere,

00:55:54.050 --> 00:55:56.870
make those in situ
measurements right there in place

00:55:56.870 --> 00:55:59.650
in the atmosphere and
see what we can learn.

00:55:59.650 --> 00:56:03.000
Not just about Venus, but about
all of the other planets out there

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:04.840
that are waiting to be discovered.

00:56:04.840 --> 00:56:06.640
So with that, thank you.

00:56:06.640 --> 00:56:19.090
