And I apologize for
going a little long,

00:56:21.360 --> 00:56:24.290
but I will definitely stand here
and answer questions for as long

00:56:24.290 --> 00:56:27.100
as you want to stand
and ask questions.

00:56:27.100 --> 00:56:30.580
&gt;&gt; I think we have two options
with our Venus exploration.

00:56:30.580 --> 00:56:35.610
One is somebody start a petition on
change.org, get enough signatures,

00:56:35.610 --> 00:56:37.320
maybe someone will listen.

00:56:37.320 --> 00:56:39.120
The other is private funding.

00:56:39.120 --> 00:56:41.830
All the billionaires
that are going to space.

00:56:41.830 --> 00:56:44.610
But questions, there may
be lots of questions,

00:56:44.610 --> 00:56:45.910
but there are no answers, right?

00:56:45.910 --> 00:56:47.210
&gt;&gt; Well, that's not true.

00:56:47.210 --> 00:56:48.730
That's not no answers.

00:56:48.730 --> 00:56:50.460
It's interesting you
mentioned the private funding

00:56:50.460 --> 00:56:53.600
because there's been a lot of
interest in sending, you know,

00:56:53.600 --> 00:56:55.650
through private funding,
sending people to Mars.

00:56:55.650 --> 00:56:58.940
There's not really-- we can't
really survive at Mars any better

00:56:58.940 --> 00:57:04.020
than we can survive at Venus right
now today honestly as humans.

00:57:04.020 --> 00:57:07.820 position:56%
And there have actually been some
interesting ideas for sending humans

00:57:07.820 --> 00:57:13.580
to Venus just on a swing-by trip,
to swing by Venus and come back,

00:57:13.580 --> 00:57:16.070
you know, kind of a geo
tours there, go out there

00:57:16.070 --> 00:57:18.050
and experience it and come back.

00:57:18.050 --> 00:57:20.780
But if you want to think
about ways to get humans

00:57:20.780 --> 00:57:25.440
out into the interstellar
or InterSolar environment,

00:57:25.440 --> 00:57:28.090
the interplanetary environment
for an extending period of time,

00:57:28.090 --> 00:57:29.390
you know, it's a possibility.

00:57:29.390 --> 00:57:31.290
We might take some
pictures along the way.

00:57:31.290 --> 00:57:32.740
Just saying.

00:57:32.740 --> 00:57:34.040
Over here, yeah?

00:57:34.040 --> 00:57:35.340
&gt;&gt; Can you talk about the dynamics

00:57:35.340 --> 00:57:37.290
of the first Russian
probe that landed?

00:57:37.290 --> 00:57:39.270
You talked about one hour.

00:57:39.270 --> 00:57:44.830 position:56%
And I assume they had to go through
some orbiter to send those pictures.

00:57:44.830 --> 00:57:48.830
If they missed that shot through
sulfuric acid atmosphere in storms

00:57:48.830 --> 00:57:51.150
and everything, it
probably wouldn't get back

00:57:51.150 --> 00:57:52.750
around to being able
to do their shot.

00:57:52.750 --> 00:57:55.080
Can you talk about what
happened and how they did that?

00:57:55.080 --> 00:57:57.540
&gt;&gt; The question here
is about the dynamics

00:57:57.540 --> 00:58:00.610
of those early Soviet
landers and how they were able

00:58:00.610 --> 00:58:03.520
to communicate their data back.

00:58:03.520 --> 00:58:06.770
Someone can correct me, but
going off the top of my brain,

00:58:06.770 --> 00:58:10.600
my recollection is those were
direct to Earth communication,

00:58:10.600 --> 00:58:12.640
as was the Pioneer
Venus large procedure.

00:58:12.640 --> 00:58:14.310
The Pioneer Venus probes
were direct to Earth.

00:58:14.310 --> 00:58:17.020
They did not communicate
through a satellite.

00:58:17.020 --> 00:58:19.600
I believe this communicated
directly back to Earth.

00:58:19.600 --> 00:58:21.590
Very low bandwidth.

00:58:21.590 --> 00:58:25.150
And you thought your
dial-up modem was slow.

00:58:25.150 --> 00:58:26.930
It was very limited.

00:58:26.930 --> 00:58:29.750
But that's my recollection
off the top of my head.

00:58:29.750 --> 00:58:32.150
That is a very challenging
thing to do.

00:58:32.150 --> 00:58:34.720
It is something that through my
mission design efforts we've looked

00:58:34.720 --> 00:58:38.780
at a lot at how you can
do that with a spacecraft

00:58:38.780 --> 00:58:40.660
and have the communication.

00:58:40.660 --> 00:58:42.000
One thing you can do is go

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:45.410
on a fly-by trajectory
as opposed to an orbit.

00:58:45.410 --> 00:58:50.150 position:56%
So that gives you an extended period
of communication time as your lander

00:58:50.150 --> 00:58:51.980
or your probe falls
to the atmosphere,

00:58:51.980 --> 00:58:54.240
and then you can continue
communicating for that hour

00:58:54.240 --> 00:58:56.260
or two or three on the surface.

00:58:56.260 --> 00:58:58.430
&gt;&gt; In the [inaudible] you
said I think five hours is

00:58:58.430 --> 00:59:00.060
where we're at now technology-wise?

00:59:00.060 --> 00:59:03.090
&gt;&gt; That's where we're at now
technology-wise, as far as cooling.

00:59:03.090 --> 00:59:05.090
I didn't get into a lot of
the mission design stuff.

00:59:05.090 --> 00:59:07.570
I'm happy to answer those
kind of questions too.

00:59:07.570 --> 00:59:12.340
Most of the thermal control, as
we're talking about the lifetimes

00:59:12.340 --> 00:59:14.350
of these landers on the surface,

00:59:14.350 --> 00:59:16.760
a lifetime of five hours
is probably limited

00:59:16.760 --> 00:59:21.530 position:56%
by how cool you can keep your lander
inside at 850 degrees outside.

00:59:21.530 --> 00:59:24.520
It's hard to keep it
cool on the inside.

00:59:24.520 --> 00:59:29.550
And with power limitations,
you can't continue

00:59:29.550 --> 00:59:31.460
to power a powered cooling system.

00:59:31.460 --> 00:59:35.120
So most of the early missions,
or all of the early missions

00:59:35.120 --> 00:59:38.570 position:56%
and everything I know of that's been
proposed to land on the surface,

00:59:38.570 --> 00:59:41.300
would use a passive
cooling, which is usually

00:59:41.300 --> 00:59:45.300
like a face change material that
would go from a solid to a liquid.

00:59:45.300 --> 00:59:49.260
And by doing that, it keeps the
inside of your pressure vessel

00:59:49.260 --> 00:59:52.400
at a constant temperature, much
like ice cubes keep your glass

00:59:52.400 --> 00:59:54.450
of water at the same temperature.

00:59:54.450 --> 00:59:57.310
And so but when all of that
face change material is melted,

00:59:57.310 --> 00:59:58.610
it's gone.

00:59:58.610 --> 01:00:02.180
So really the limitation there
for five hours is how much

01:00:02.180 --> 01:00:06.300
of that face change material
can you bring with you?

