01:01:13.230 --> 01:01:15.830
but not like a huge
crowdsourced funding.

01:01:15.830 --> 01:01:21.320
I can't really speak to other
types of publicly-funded things

01:01:21.320 --> 01:01:23.090
and where you draw
the line between NASA.

01:01:23.090 --> 01:01:27.410
That's kind of out of my, not only
my area of interest in experience,

01:01:27.410 --> 01:01:30.260
but also out of my
authority to speak on.

01:01:30.260 --> 01:01:31.560
So I apologize for that.

01:01:31.560 --> 01:01:33.800
I can talk to you maybe a little
more after if you're interested.

01:01:33.800 --> 01:01:36.470
There was another question right
here, and then we'll move around.

01:01:36.470 --> 01:01:49.290
&gt;&gt; If the cooling is your
issue, I suppose that's

01:01:49.290 --> 01:01:53.490
because the electronics maybe
[inaudible] or whatever,

01:01:53.490 --> 01:01:57.540
is it possible to develop
high pressure electronic

01:01:57.540 --> 01:01:59.020
like your ceramics or?

01:01:59.020 --> 01:02:03.430 position:56%
&gt;&gt; This is a great question about
how do we solve the thermal problem?

01:02:03.430 --> 01:02:08.570
Is it all just cooling, or can
you also develop things that work

01:02:08.570 --> 01:02:10.780 position:56%
in the high temperature environment?

01:02:10.780 --> 01:02:12.080
Great question.

01:02:12.080 --> 01:02:13.380
Yes, it could work.

01:02:13.380 --> 01:02:17.020
We actually-- NASA has a funded
program right now called Hot Tech,

01:02:17.020 --> 01:02:19.580
which is specifically
focused on trying

01:02:19.580 --> 01:02:24.220
to develop high temperature
electronics, which is great.

01:02:24.220 --> 01:02:28.270
We already-- I know of already a
seismometer that's been developed

01:02:28.270 --> 01:02:33.320
that could actually function on
the surface of Venus for a month

01:02:33.320 --> 01:02:36.020
under high temperature conditions.

01:02:36.020 --> 01:02:41.210
The problem is we've got the
high temperature electronics,

01:02:41.210 --> 01:02:44.650
the soldering and the
electronics work,

01:02:44.650 --> 01:02:49.710
but we don't have memory systems,
we don't have transmission systems,

01:02:49.710 --> 01:02:53.750
we don't have, you know, we
don't have the data storage

01:02:53.750 --> 01:02:57.330
and the communication capacity
to get the data off the surface.

01:02:57.330 --> 01:02:58.920
So there's still a lot
of investment and work

01:02:58.920 --> 01:03:00.220
that needs to be done there.

01:03:00.220 --> 01:03:01.520
NASA is investing in that.

01:03:01.520 --> 01:03:02.820
There's others that are
investing in it as well.

01:03:02.820 --> 01:03:04.120
A lot of universities are
doing research in that area.

01:03:04.120 --> 01:03:05.420
And so my guess is that
somewhere along the line,

01:03:05.420 --> 01:03:06.720
the two will meet in the middle.

01:03:06.720 --> 01:03:08.020
We'll have things that can
survive to higher temperatures,

01:03:08.020 --> 01:03:09.320
and we'll find better ways to
encapsulate things to keep them

01:03:09.320 --> 01:03:10.620
in the range of temperatures
where they need to be.

01:03:10.620 --> 01:03:11.920
But it's a great question.

01:03:11.920 --> 01:03:13.220
It's something that
is being worked on.

01:03:13.220 --> 01:03:14.520
It's not ready to fly
today, but someday.

