Okay, so the question is how
deep is the Venus atmosphere,

01:03:27.420 --> 01:03:29.730
and how does that compare to Earth?

01:03:29.730 --> 01:03:34.070
So the cloud tops on Venus
are at about 70 kilometers,

01:03:34.070 --> 01:03:39.810
so quickly in my mind, 40
miles ish, 35, 40 miles.

01:03:39.810 --> 01:03:43.610
It's pretty big compared
to Earth's atmosphere.

01:03:43.610 --> 01:03:45.390
It's much bigger than
Earth's atmosphere.

01:03:45.390 --> 01:03:51.020 position:56%
And when you-- it's pretty dense
even at higher altitudes than Earth.

01:03:51.020 --> 01:03:54.690
It's pretty stable in that
density at the high altitudes.

01:03:54.690 --> 01:03:58.000
Because as they said, it gets
up, the Sun coming in on it

01:03:58.000 --> 01:03:59.810
for hundreds and hundreds of days.

01:03:59.810 --> 01:04:01.160
So it's pretty stable.

01:04:01.160 --> 01:04:06.260
So then the second part
of the question had to do

01:04:06.260 --> 01:04:09.040
with how far does the
heat radiate out?

01:04:09.040 --> 01:04:10.340
That's a good question.

01:04:10.340 --> 01:04:12.310
And honestly, that's something
I'll have to go back and research

01:04:12.310 --> 01:04:15.430
because I don't know the
answer off the top of my head.

01:04:15.430 --> 01:04:19.810 position:56%
I do know that spacecraft that are
in orbit a couple hundred kilometers

01:04:19.810 --> 01:04:22.920
above the surface do have to deal
with that radiation, absolutely,

01:04:22.920 --> 01:04:24.220
that comes off the planet.

01:04:24.220 --> 01:04:25.520
It's pretty bright.

01:04:25.520 --> 01:04:26.820
The clouds are really bright.

01:04:26.820 --> 01:04:29.890
There's a lot of radiation that
