&gt;&gt; Right.

01:04:48.170 --> 01:04:50.450
&gt;&gt; Now, if it doesn't
have any plates,

01:04:50.450 --> 01:04:54.220
how are the volcanoes created?

01:04:54.220 --> 01:04:56.640
&gt;&gt; So great question.

01:04:56.640 --> 01:04:59.670
So the question is, if
there's no plates on Venus,

01:04:59.670 --> 01:05:02.680
so it doesn't have plate tectonics,
how are the volcanoes created?

01:05:02.680 --> 01:05:04.660
Well, this is a good question.

01:05:04.660 --> 01:05:09.340
On Earth, we do have volcanoes
that are not on plate boundaries.

01:05:09.340 --> 01:05:10.640
We have a few, right?

01:05:10.640 --> 01:05:12.620
We know Hawaii is a great example

01:05:12.620 --> 01:05:14.840
of a volcano that's not
on a plate boundary.

01:05:14.840 --> 01:05:17.390
It's actually what we
call a hot spot volcano.

01:05:17.390 --> 01:05:20.170
It's fed directly from
Earth's mantle.

01:05:20.170 --> 01:05:22.670
Magma comes straight
up through the crust,

01:05:22.670 --> 01:05:25.650
right out onto the sea
floor, and now Hawaii.

01:05:25.650 --> 01:05:29.010
&gt;&gt; But there should
be a hole somewhere.

01:05:29.010 --> 01:05:31.550
&gt;&gt; Yes, there is a hole
somewhere, definitely.

01:05:31.550 --> 01:05:34.000
And on Venus, there are holes.

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:35.930
And the models that we have

01:05:35.930 --> 01:05:41.230
for Venus are what we call these
heat pipe or hot spot volcanoes

01:05:41.230 --> 01:05:45.060
where the heat pipes are
delivering the magma and the heat

01:05:45.060 --> 01:05:49.690
from the interior, right, from this
mantle layer out to the surface.

01:05:49.690 --> 01:05:53.060
And so then there's a hole in
the volcanoes, the lava comes

01:05:53.060 --> 01:05:56.050
out from the vent at the surface.

01:05:56.050 --> 01:05:57.840 position:56%
But again, these are pretty limited.

01:05:57.840 --> 01:06:01.370
If you want to look at how you can
get rid of heat from the inside

01:06:01.370 --> 01:06:03.260
of a planet, they're
pretty inefficient

01:06:03.260 --> 01:06:07.390
to just lose it during these
individual heat pipes as opposed

01:06:07.390 --> 01:06:08.690
to the kind of plate boundaries

01:06:08.690 --> 01:06:12.020
where we just unzip the whole
Atlantic Ocean and lava comes

01:06:12.020 --> 01:06:15.630
out all along the whole thing.

01:06:15.630 --> 01:06:16.930
A question back here?

01:06:16.930 --> 01:06:28.480
&gt;&gt; I found it interesting that
the planet spins a lot more slowly

01:06:28.480 --> 01:06:30.360
than its atmosphere.

01:06:30.360 --> 01:06:45.300 position:56%
And I wonder if there's any evidence
of, over time, the slowing of Venus,

01:06:45.300 --> 01:06:55.200
maybe because of gravitation,
because maybe all of the gravity is

01:06:55.200 --> 01:07:03.500
at the Sun and we're faster
because we have a lot of gravity

01:07:03.500 --> 01:07:07.350
on the other side, and
whether that has any leverage

01:07:07.350 --> 01:07:11.080
for explaining maybe the newness
of the surface, maybe building

01:07:11.080 --> 01:07:12.780
on the gentleman's question,

01:07:12.780 --> 01:07:15.590
if things inside are spinning
either faster or slower over time,

01:07:15.590 --> 01:07:19.690
whether sort of the hot
spots can form in that way,

01:07:19.690 --> 01:07:22.430
and whether if we can
speed it up again,

01:07:22.430 --> 01:07:28.260
whether we can spin off the
atmosphere and make it happen.

01:07:28.260 --> 01:07:29.560
&gt;&gt; Hmm, speed it up.

01:07:29.560 --> 01:07:31.900
Well, that might be challenging.

01:07:31.900 --> 01:07:33.200
&gt;&gt; A lot of energy.

01:07:33.200 --> 01:07:35.480
&gt;&gt; The question has
to do with, you know,

01:07:35.480 --> 01:07:42.350
how fast the atmosphere is
rotating relative to the surface,

01:07:42.350 --> 01:07:45.500
and all of the other tentacles
that hang off of that as far

01:07:45.500 --> 01:07:51.390
as implications for, you know,
how these volcanoes are forming

01:07:51.390 --> 01:07:56.530
and how planets in general feed
volcanism through these kind

01:07:56.530 --> 01:07:59.380
of dynamics that go
on inside the planet.

01:07:59.380 --> 01:08:02.690
And the answer to the first
part of your question is

01:08:02.690 --> 01:08:07.910
that over the lifetime of the
missions we've had at Venus,

01:08:07.910 --> 01:08:13.420
decades now with Magellan and
Venus Express and Akatsuki,

01:08:13.420 --> 01:08:20.720
there have been a couple
papers, and I'm going to try

01:08:20.720 --> 01:08:24.750
to remember the details, and
I probably can't fish them

01:08:24.750 --> 01:08:29.810
out right here on the spot,
but there was a potential

01:08:29.810 --> 01:08:36.930
that they saw some change in
the rotation rate over time.

01:08:36.930 --> 01:08:46.080
But then there was another
paper that came out that kind

01:08:46.080 --> 01:08:49.300
of discredited some
of that because some

01:08:49.300 --> 01:08:51.730
of the assumptions
weren't quite right.

01:08:51.730 --> 01:08:55.990
So again, it's kind of
being debated whether

01:08:55.990 --> 01:08:59.390
or not its spin rate
is changing over time.

01:08:59.390 --> 01:09:00.930
It's still kind of out
there in the debate,

01:09:00.930 --> 01:09:03.520
but it's possible that
it may be changing.

01:09:03.520 --> 01:09:06.790
And honestly, I don't remember if
it's speeding up or slowing down.

01:09:06.790 --> 01:09:09.360
I'd have to go back and check that.

01:09:09.360 --> 01:09:11.760
But there's a possibility
that it is changing.

01:09:11.760 --> 01:09:18.030
Whether or not you could spin
up the planet again and try

01:09:18.030 --> 01:09:22.130
