01:11:28.300 --> 01:11:56.260
[ Inaudible ]

01:11:56.260 --> 01:11:59.270
Correct. So the question is, what
kind of technology are we using

01:11:59.270 --> 01:12:01.080
on the proposed Vicky mission

01:12:01.080 --> 01:12:03.710
to survive this harsh
environment near the surface?

01:12:03.710 --> 01:12:05.790
If you want to land and
survive on the surface,

01:12:05.790 --> 01:12:07.550
how are you going to do that?

01:12:07.550 --> 01:12:12.880
So in all honesty, the technology
required is not that fancy.

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:18.140
We have a very, a pressure vessel,
which is similar to the types

01:12:18.140 --> 01:12:20.960
of bathometers and stuff
that we send under the ocean

01:12:20.960 --> 01:12:23.600
that can withstand great
pressures on their exteriors.

01:12:23.600 --> 01:12:26.460
It's spherical in shape, which
is a good shape for trying

01:12:26.460 --> 01:12:28.530 position:56%
to fend off lots of great pressures.

01:12:28.530 --> 01:12:33.190
We do have some more modern
ceiling technology than was used

01:12:33.190 --> 01:12:35.330
on the older ones that
should help us keep

01:12:35.330 --> 01:12:38.790
from getting any kind of leaks.

01:12:38.790 --> 01:12:41.530
But then the kind of cooling
technology is, as I've described,

01:12:41.530 --> 01:12:45.870
a passive system with a face
change material, power sources

01:12:45.870 --> 01:12:48.830
or batteries, your
typical kinds of batteries.

01:12:48.830 --> 01:12:51.130
We didn't talk about
power too much in here,

01:12:51.130 --> 01:12:55.010
but nuclear power sources
could be used on Venus,

01:12:55.010 --> 01:12:56.510
but they're not very efficient

01:12:56.510 --> 01:12:58.500
because nuclear power
sources require you

01:12:58.500 --> 01:13:00.600
to dump and dissipate heat.

01:13:00.600 --> 01:13:01.900
And trying to dissipate heat

01:13:01.900 --> 01:13:05.920
into Venus's atmosphere,
not very efficient.

01:13:05.920 --> 01:13:11.420
So in all honesty, the technology
doesn't require that much advance.

01:13:11.420 --> 01:13:15.500
We have the technology available
today to do that sort of thing.

01:13:15.500 --> 01:13:19.700
We are flying some very
sensitive instrumentation.

01:13:19.700 --> 01:13:22.690 position:56%
A lot of the instruments we'd like
to carry to Venus, on either DAVINCI

01:13:22.690 --> 01:13:25.580
or Vicky, are the same types of
instruments that are operating

01:13:25.580 --> 01:13:28.260
on the surface of Mars now,
the same types of measurements

01:13:28.260 --> 01:13:30.730
that are making great
discoveries every day

01:13:30.730 --> 01:13:34.150
about the Martian environment
and the curiosity landing site.

01:13:34.150 --> 01:13:35.450
Those are the same instruments

01:13:35.450 --> 01:13:38.360
that we're proposing to
carry on our mission.

01:13:38.360 --> 01:13:42.760
The biggest thing is trying
to survive the entry loads.

01:13:42.760 --> 01:13:45.530
And so there are new
technologies for trying

01:13:45.530 --> 01:13:48.630
to enter the Venus atmosphere
to keep you protected

01:13:48.630 --> 01:13:49.940 position:56%
from that atmosphere as you come in.

01:13:49.940 --> 01:13:53.590
And that's probably where the
greatest technology development has

01:13:53.590 --> 01:13:57.480
been that allows us to come
in at low angles on the top

01:13:57.480 --> 01:14:00.270
of the atmosphere to
reduce the G loads on all

01:14:00.270 --> 01:14:02.500
of those sensitive instruments.

01:14:02.500 --> 01:14:04.670
Yeah, I think Pioneer
Venus came in at

01:14:04.670 --> 01:14:06.640
like 300 G or something like that.

01:14:06.640 --> 01:14:12.300
I mean, it's outrageous, you
know, G shock that it got coming

01:14:12.300 --> 01:14:13.900
into the top of the
Venus atmosphere.

01:14:13.900 --> 01:14:16.450
And most of our instrument probably
wouldn't like that very much.

01:14:16.450 --> 01:14:20.430
So we try and keep it much,
much lower than that, yeah.

